      <div align="center">
        <p><font color="303881" size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><font color="#333333"><strong><font size="4">Blood-letting in the monastery: Health care or &lsquo;doorway to heaven&rsquo;? </font><br>
          <br>
        </strong> <font size="3">Alfons Zettler (Universit&auml;t Dortmund)</font></font></font></p>
      </div>
    <!-- InstanceEndEditable --><!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Text" -->
      <p><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">In this paper I will examine the habit of blood-letting in medieval monastic communities. &nbsp;Based upon much evidence, we know that in late-antique societies blood-letting was already a fairly wide-spread method of medical treatment and health care, particularly among the upper-classes.&nbsp; Accordingly, the procedure is often mentioned in the medical treatises of that time. On the other hand, only a very small number of sources about blood-letting have come down to us from the earlier and central middle ages. As a result, it is very difficult to determine whetherblood-letting continued to be similarly popular and to what extent it was known and accepted as medical treatment by early medieval society. </font></p>
      <p><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Among the small range of early medieval documents which mention blood-letting are Bede&rsquo;s &lsquo;De minutione sanguinis sive De phlebotomia&rsquo; (before 735), the Salernitan &lsquo;Regimen sanitatis&rsquo; (before 1250) and the famous St. Gall Plan (before 830), which contains the drawing of a complete early medieval monastery. The Plan also includes some 330 explanatory inscriptions, including one which clearly indicates a separate &lsquo;House for blood-letting&rsquo; among its buildings. This Houseis situated in the left upper corner of the Plan, next to the &lsquo;House of the physicians&rsquo; and the infirmary, the monks&rsquo; hospital. </font></p>
      <p><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Obviously, the scarcity of documents on blood-lettingand theintriguing building on the Carolingian St. Gall Plan pose quite a number of problems and questions, some of which will be investigated in this paper. I will primarily focus upon the monastic aspects of the question, but I will also try to examine blood-letting as a phenomenon of medieval feudal society in general. &nbsp;</font></p>
